**Data Analysis Project**

This week's programming assignment involves analyzing an array of stock opening prices represented as floating-point numbers and spanning 10 days. The project includes screenshots of code and explanations, followed by the full source code at the end. This document will adhere to the specified order of instructions.

**Calculate the average stock price:**

![image](https://github.com/ThutaCodes/Java-Projects/assets/157232035/4c83f7be-f95f-485c-af88-0ecb9e35bff0)

The first line of code is importing a specific class from Java’s built-in library called java.util. In this case, it’s importing the ArrayList class.

Java class named **Main**, contains a method called **calculateAveragePrice** which takes in an array of floating-point numbers (**float\[\] prices**) representing stock prices. It initializes a variable **sum** to zero to keep track of the total sum of all the stock prices. It uses a **for** loop to go through each **price** in the **prices** array. Inside the loop, it adds each **price** to the **sum** variable. After looping through all the prices, it returns the average price by dividing the **sum** by the number of prices in the array (**prices.length**). This method calculates the average stock price by summing up all the prices in the array and then dividing that sum by the total number of prices in the array.

**Find the maximum stock price:**

![image](https://github.com/ThutaCodes/Java-Projects/assets/157232035/caec838a-0dca-4447-9adf-359bb52a42ac)

The method **findMaximumPrice** takes an array of stock prices (**float\[\] prices**) as input. It initializes a variable **maxPrice** with the first element of the array. It then loops through each price in the array. For each price, it compares it with the current maximum price (**maxPrice**). If the current price is greater than the current maximum price, it updates **maxPrice** to that price. Finally, it returns the maximum price found in the array after looping through all the prices.

**Determine the occurrence count of a specific price:**

![image](https://github.com/ThutaCodes/Java-Projects/assets/157232035/df494035-6b56-4e08-a08e-7fbf709ecaee)

This code defines a method named **countOccurrences** that takes in two parameters: **prices**: An array of floating-point numbers representing stock prices and **targetPrice**: The specific price whose occurrences need to be counted in the array.

This method initializes a variable **count** to keep track of how many times the **targetPrice** occurs in the array. The **for** loop iterates through each element (**price**) in the **prices** array. For each element, it checks if the **price** matches the **targetPrice**. If there's a match, it increments the **count** variable by 1. Finally, it returns the total count of occurrences of the **targetPrice** in the array.

**Compute the cumulative sum of stock prices:**

![image](https://github.com/ThutaCodes/Java-Projects/assets/157232035/7bc0d786-cc9f-4d13-8080-b35e90195492)

This code calculates the running total of stock prices in the ArrayList, where each element in the new ArrayList (**cumulativeSum**) is the sum of all the prices up to that point in the original ArrayList (**prices**). **computeCumulativeSum** method takes in an ArrayList called **prices** containing stock prices as input. It initializes a new ArrayList called **cumulativeSum** to store the cumulative sums of the prices. ‘sum’ is initialized to zero to hold the running sum of prices. It loops through each **price** in the **prices** ArrayList. For each price, it adds that price to the **sum** and then adds the current **sum** to the **cumulativeSum** ArrayList. Finally, it returns the **cumulativeSum** ArrayList containing the cumulative sums of the stock prices.

**Initializing the sample Array**

![image](https://github.com/ThutaCodes/Java-Projects/assets/157232035/99fac9ac-312f-4d56-97e8-ca2b87413b88)

The **ArrayList** named **stockPricesArrayList** is initialized. This **ArrayList** will store the same set of stock prices as the array. The **for** loop iterates through each value in the **stockPricesArray** and adds it to the **stockPricesArrayList**. This helps in converting the array into an **ArrayList** for further manipulation or analysis using the more flexible features of an **ArrayList**. This code initializes an array with 10 days of stock prices.

**Printing out the values**

![image](https://github.com/ThutaCodes/Java-Projects/assets/157232035/8b65524e-6b64-49b8-8948-46675fdae53e)

This part of the code calculates the average (mean) stock price using the calculateAveragePrice method, passing in an array (stockPricesArray) containing stock prices. The result, the average price, is stored in the averagePrice variable and then printed out.

![image](https://github.com/ThutaCodes/Java-Projects/assets/157232035/012a8b0a-7a2a-41a9-8fe0-5f29ae44787f)

This section counts how many times a specific price (**targetPrice**, which is set to 3153.42, which is also that highest value in the array) appears in the stockPricesArray. It uses the **countOccurrences** method, passing in the array and the target price. The number of occurrences is stored in the occurrences variable and then printed.

![image](https://github.com/ThutaCodes/Java-Projects/assets/157232035/09ea1d80-7e22-42b1-95a0-37f0638c527a)

Finally, this part calculates the cumulative sum of stock prices stored in an **ArrayList** (**stockPricesArrayList**). It uses the **computeCumulativeSum** method to compute this sum and stores the result in the **cumulativeSum** variable. Then, it's printed out.
